review_blob: The alcohol in this beer is mostly a pure ethanol additive. I wouldnt recommend it. http://thebeercast.com/2014/05/brewmeister-lies.ht
Dark ale with a chocolatey flavour as is often the case from Dram! Nothing special.
Despite the name, this is actually a very subtle flavoured beer that is very light and very very drinkable. A pleasure.
A sweet golden ale, not particularly great. I had it from the bottle not the cask.
Not as a good as the Fortyniner as far as bottled beers go. Stronger too. Available in Scottish supermarkets no less.
Pretty impressive for a bottled ale and a nice and light at 3.6%. Nice reddish brown colour. Can be found in Scottish supermarkets.
beer_name: Wyre Piddle Piddle in the Hole (Bottle)

review_blob: A classic English ale thats as good as the best. Enjoyable both from the cask and the bottle.
Weird beer. Its got a lime green colour, very light, refreshing, but also has a lime taste, which is just a bit weird, even in a golden summer ale.

I had this at the Kirkstyle Inn last weekend - so is hardly retired! The Lake District has always brewed some of the best dark ales and this is no exception, dark in appearance, but lighter, fruiter flavour. Id never get bored of this one.
A great beer from Oxfordshire. Reliable in cask and bottle. Smooth flavour.
My favourite beer when I lived in Hampshire. A dark amber ale with a lovely flavour enjoyable both form the cask and the bottle.
Totally typical red ale from Scotland, being in a bottle its a bit fizzier than a cask ale.
Nice and frothy summer ale. Only had a half but its another reliable beer from Cairngorm.
A good summer session ale, with a nice light, cloudy colour and sediment floating in the bottom.
Reliable choice from the tap in the Porterhouse if you get tired off the more unusual beers.
Can find it everywhere in Edinburgh - harder in Glasgow - but for a common ale its nae bad.
Unusual dark ale. Very drinkable solid offering from Caledonian. Would choose again.
Best in Dublin. Less smooth than Murphys. A reliable beer but nothing that exciting.
Better than Guinness but you cannae find it nowhere no more. Maybe the Murphys bar in Glasgows Waxy O Conners.
Pretty good for an American beer - but then again they did learn a thing or two from Shepheard Neame.
Light as in low alcohol, which makes a good choice, but unfortunately the flavour was very disappointing.
Very enjoyable choice of ale down the Cloisters in Edinburgh - boy do I miss Edinburgh sometimes.
Awesome in Dublin - not so great in London. Very strong, sweet flavour, lovely colour.
This beer varies a lot - sometimes great, sometimes awful. Used to drink in Southampton in Cask form.
One of the best Scottish reds - you can always rely on Orkney to produce nice beers.
Enjoyable Scottish Red - but I cant find it anymore. Where is it in Scotland? :-(
Only drink this at its best in London - elsewhere it can be bad. Great when good.
Only had this beer once, but I really enjoyed it - will look after it again.
One of the best Scottish ales. A summer ale that has a pretty good flavour.
An old favourite when I was living down South - reliable if nothing particularly special.
Reliable pint of heavy generally only found around London - used to be a regular choice of mine.
Watery, not particular pleasant lager that is best consume over a souvla in the Cypriot heat...
A very reliable tasty ale you can find in many pubs in England and even a few places in Scotland - the best thing Greene King makes.
The best bottled ale Ive ever drunk. Shame its only available for such a limited time and where to buy in Scotland?
So much of these details make sense now - "Previously known as 70/-", "Belhaven (Greene King)" - this is a poor quality bitter that you find everywhere and gives bitter a bad name. Avoid.

A very average lager that you will typically find in Thai restaurants. Nothing that really stands out.
A very good Thai lager. Found in most Thai restaurants. Has a malty ale-like flavour.
Very dull watery lager - I always go with OB instead when in a Korean, which has much more falvour
I like OB. Its the best Korean beer. Its good for a lager. Has some malty flavours like youd find in ale. Can be found in Korean restaurants, such as Shilla in Glasgow.
